      "content": "Students can frame border control through the lens of the social contract theory, arguing that citizens consent to be governed in exchange for the state's protection and orderly function. If a state cannot control its external borders, it fundamentally risks undermining the internal security and predictability upon which that contract is built. Therefore, enforcing strict entry rules is presented not merely as a policy preference, but as a necessary guarantor of the state's ability to provide its guaranteed protections to its lawful constituents. This positions enforcement as a duty to uphold the very basis of civil society.",
